Globalization's Diseases
Globalization is being put to its severest test ever.
Its tensions are simmering everywhere.
The vast majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling economically in decline.
The North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk another recession.
The war now threatens in Iraq.
For proponents of open markets and free trade, this situation presents major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why do its advantages seem concentrated in only a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they barely suffice.
Certain regions of the world have greatly benefited from globalization in recent years, particularly East Asia and China.
However, some regions have only benefitted marginally, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa.
The U.S. government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they face.
The slow growth of Africa, American leaders assert, is caused by the inadequacy of African governments.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the last two decades while many Asian countries that ranked among the worst in international government effectiveness comparisons (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
The countries with large populations and thus large domestic markets tend to grow more rapidly than countries with small populations.
(As with all such economic trends, there are counterexamples).
Coastal countries tend to be more performant than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries that border rich markets, like Mexico, tend to be more performant than countries that are far from the major markets.
Ces différences revêtent une grande importance.
If wealthy countries do not care much about these structural problems, the gaps between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries shift responsibility onto unlucky countries by claiming they are in some way culturally or politically unfit to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify tensions.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to move towards a more serious approach to globalization than that offered by wealthy countries, particularly America.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely addressing the fundamental needs of the world's poorest peoples.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated primarily through better governance within their own countries.
But in others, an honest look at the gathered evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty involve diseases, climate instability, poor soils, distances to markets, and so on.
A genuine assessment would show further that the poorest countries lack the ability to gather sufficient funds to resolve such issues on their own.
Rather than seeing rich countries give more lectures on bad governance in poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries offer sufficient financial aid to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
A striking example illustrates this situation.
Controlling diseases requires a health system capable of providing life-saving medications and basic preventive services such as bed nets to fight malaria and vitamins to combat nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least approximately 40 dollars per person and per year.
This amount represents just a speck of sand for rich countries that spend systematically more than 2,000 dollars per person and per year on health, but it exceeds the reach of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of 200 dollars per person.
A functioning health system would cost more than the entire revenue of its government!
Even if Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases until it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of scolding the poor for their "sins," we must offer prudent diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and each region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that hinder their growth and economic development.
In regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem primarily stems from geographic isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and internet connectivity to help these remote regions establish productive ties with the world.
The rich countries must contribute to financing these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges concern disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Aid from abroad is once again required on a larger scale.
In other regions, the major problems revolve around a lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the inherent complexities of globalization seriously.
The one-size-fits-all Washington Consensus ideology is outdated.
On the brink of war, it is urgent to tackle the hard task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders from the rich and if we mobilize partnerships between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
